title: Reduce number of DNS lookups on the broker
body:
Reduce the number of DNS lookups done by the broker by reusing the same
values for all future ServerInstance creation. Since we do a DNS lookup
anyway when increasing the size of the broker's connection pool, this
does not cause issues even if the DNS entry changes.

The JVM actually has a cache for DNS entries, but accessing it requires
a synchronization block; as such, this can reduce contention for
accessing the JVM cache. Furthermore, these changes remove a DNS lookup
per server for each result coming from a realtime server during hybrid
queries. This also removes most DNS lookups when processing live
instance changes on the broker.

title: [PINOT-4602] Changed servers to re-use segment files if available, when asked to re-commit an LLC segment
body:
It can happen that a servers overshoot the lease (due to GC, for example) and we end up with the controller
asking a server to commit the segment again. In that case, if the offset is still the same, we keep the tar
file around and re-use it when committing the segment.

We take care to remove the tar file when we go ONLINE for a segment, so that old files are cleaned up.

Instead, we return Integer.MIN_VALUE. This value gets written to the segment metadata when the segment is sealed.

When loading the metadata, we want to ensure that the bad number is not used for any processing, so we throw an
exception when it is accessed

title: [TE] Refined Dimensional alert grouping logic
body:
There are two purposes of multidimensional alert grouping: 1. Reduce the number of emails that are sent out. 2. Provide an overview of the anomalies in the system.

In this PR, we use a simple method to group anomalies by different dimensions, which solve problem 1 and provide the potential solution for problem 2.

The followings are the changes to current ThirdEye:
1. Remove generic template for alert group key. Because we haven't decided the right way to solve the problem. Thus, it is too early to optimize (generalize) the interface.
2. Add GroupedAnomalyDTO for storing the grouped anomaly.
3. Add HorizontalAlertGrouper for grouping anomalies in different dimensions.
4. Add time based merge logic for grouped anomalies.
5. Add alert for grouped anomalies. We currently implement a size severity filter, which use the number of merged anomalies in the grouped anomalies as its severity and determines if the grouped anomalies is qualified for alerting.

Tested on a local box, which sends alerts for 1 week. The number of alerts has been reduced to 30% of the original number.

title: [PINOT-4885] Change FixedByteSingleColumnMultiValueReaderWriter to expand header section dynamically
body:
Changed FixedByteSingleColumnMultiValueReaderWriter so that the header sections also expands like the data
section, so that we don't have to allocate data for max number of rows in the beginning.

For now, the same allocation is maintained so that we don't see any change in the behavior in production.

This, and the next few PRs should help us limit consumption by memory (instead of by number of rows) or time,
making it easier to configure real-time service in pinot.

title: Avoid creating unnecessary garbage during realtime indexing.
body:
1. Instead of creating a new ArrayList for dimension and metric names,
caches those, as they are requested for each row being indexed.

2. Avoid creating MD5 hash of the schema for each row being indexed.
Since schema changes are not that frequent, it is OK to have a linear
search in small sized list, as opposed to creating a map with MD5 string
has the key.

When consuming at several thousand events per second, these could produce
few GB's of garbage within several seconds. This change eliminates
that garbage generation.
